<DESCRIPT>  COMPANY; MERGER  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  The Procter &amp; Gamble Co. said it has bought a Czechoslovakian maker of
cleaning products for $20 million and promised to spend $24 million in four
years to modernize the plant.;   P&amp;G said it purchased Rakona Co. of Rakovnic,
Czechoslovakia, from the Czech Republic. P&amp;G had announced an agreement in
principle with the Czech Ministry of Privatization on June 19.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Business  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  PROCTER &amp; GAMBLE BUYS CZECHOSLOVAKIAN FIRM  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>     Rakona produces detergents and other cleaning products. P&amp;G officials said
they are committed to improving and modernizing the plant, maintaining
employment there and establishing exports.;   Procter &amp; Gamble, a consumer
products company based in Cincinnati, had worldwide sales of $27 billion in
the fiscal year ended June 30. The company, which has been expanding its
international business, maintains plants or offices in 50 countries and does
business in more than 140 nations.  </TEXT>
